2026-05-10 22:40:39 [DEBUG] openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-242fcdc6-aa88-4d1d-86e6-f2a10b248699', 'security': {'bearer_auth': True}, 'content': None, 'json_data': {'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': 'Generate a pytest test file (test_capstone.py) for a capstone project.\n\n── Interfaces ──\n"""\nThis module defines the abstract interfaces for the MiniGPT capstone project.\n\nIt establishes a clear contract for each core component of the system using\nPython\'s `abc` (Abstract Base Class) module. This approach ensures that any\nconcrete implementation of these components will adhere to a consistent API,\nmaking the system modular, testable, and easier to reason about.\n\nThe defined interfaces are:\n- MiniGPTConfig: A dataclass for model hyperparameters.\n- MiniGPTModel: An abstract interface for the GPT model itself.\n- MiniTextDataLoader: An abstract interface for handling data loading and batching.\n- MiniTrainer: An abstract interface for the training and evaluation loop.\n"""\n\nfrom abc import ABC, abstractmethod\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom typing import Optional, Tuple\n\nimport torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\n\n# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# Configuration\n# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n@dataclass\nclass MiniGPTConfig:\n    """\n    A dataclass holding all essential hyperparameters for the MiniGPT model.\n\n    This class serves as a single source of truth for the model\'s architecture\n    and training configuration. It is not an ABC but a concrete dataclass\n    intended to be passed to the model and other components during initialization.\n\n    Attributes:\n        block_size (int): The maximum sequence length (context size) for the model.\n        vocab_size (int): The number of unique tokens in the vocabulary.\n        n_layer (int): The number of transformer blocks in the model.\n        n_head (int): The number of attention heads in the multi-head attention mechanism.\n        n_embd (int): The dimensionality of the token embeddings and model\'s hidden states.\n        dropout (float): The dropout rate used for regularization.\n    """\n    block_size: int = 256\n    vocab_size: int = 50257  # GPT-2 vocab size\n    n_layer: int = 6\n    n_head: int = 6\n    n_embd: int = 384\n    dropout: float = 0.1\n\n\n# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# Model Interface\n# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nclass MiniGPTModel(nn.Module, ABC):\n    """\n    Abstract base class for a simplified GPT model.\n\n    This interface defines the essential methods for a transformer-based language\n    model, including initialization from a config, a forward pass to compute\n    logits, and a generation method for autoregressive text synthesis.\n    """\n\n    @abstractmethod\n    def __init__(self, config: MiniGPTConfig):\n        """\n        Initializes the model architecture based on the provided configuration.\n\n        The contract:\n        - Must call `super().__init__()`.\n        - Must store the `config` object.\n        - Must create all necessary layers (embedding, transformer blocks, final layer norm,\n          and language model head) as attributes of the class.\n\n        Args:\n            config (MiniGPTConfig): An object containing the model\'s hyperparameters.\n        """\n        # TODO: Implement this\n        raise NotImplementedError("The __init__ method must be implemented by a subclass.")\n\n    @abstractmethod\n    def forward(self,\n                idx: torch.Tensor,\n                targets: Optional[torch.Tensor] = None\n                ) -> tuple[torch.Tensor, Optional[torch.Tensor]]:\n        """\n        Performs a forward pass through the model.\n\n        The contract:\n        - Takes a batch of token sequences (`idx`) as input.\n        - Computes the logits for the next token prediction at each position.\n        - If `targets` are provided, it must also compute and return the cross-entropy loss.\n        - The shape of the input `idx` tensor is (batch_size, block_size).\n        - The shape of the returned `logits` tensor must be (batch_size, block_size, vocab_size).\n        - If `targets` are provided, the returned `loss` should be a scalar tensor.\n\n        Args:\n            idx (torch.Tensor): A tensor of token indices of shape (B, T).\n            targets (Optional[torch.Tensor]): A tensor of target indices of shape (B, T).\n                                             If provided, the loss is calculated.\n\n        Returns:\n            tuple[torch.Tensor, Optional[torch.Tensor]]: A tuple containing:\n                - logits: The model\'s output scores for each token in the vocabulary.\n                - loss: The calculated cross-entropy loss if targets are provided, else None.\n        """\n        # TODO: Implement this\n        raise NotImplementedError("The forward method must be implemented by a subclass.")\n\n    @abstractmethod\n    @torch.no_grad()\n    def generate(self,\n                 idx: torch.Tensor,\n                 max_new_tokens: int,\n                 temperature: float = 1.0,\n                 top_k: Optional[int] = None\n                 ) -> torch.Tensor:\n        """\n        Generates a sequence of new tokens autoregressively.\n\n        The contract:\n        - Must operate in `torch.no_grad()` mode for efficiency.\n        - Takes an initial sequence of tokens (`idx`) as a prompt.\n        - Iteratively generates `max_new_tokens` one by one, appending each new\n          token to the sequence and using the updated sequence as input for the next step.\n        - The context (`idx`) must be cropped to `block_size` if it exceeds this length.\n        - Must implement temperature scaling for sampling.\n        - Must optionally implement top-k sampling.\n        - Must return a tensor containing the original `idx` plus the generated tokens.\n        - The shape of the input `idx` tensor is (B, T).\n        - The shape of the returned tensor must be (B, T + max_new_tokens).\n\n        Args:\n            idx (torch.Tensor): The initial context or prompt (B, T).\n            max_new_tokens (int): The number of new tokens to generate.\n            temperature (float): Scaling factor for logits; >1.0 for more randomness,\n                                 <1.0 for more determinism.\n            top_k (Optional[int]): If set, sample only from the `k` most likely tokens.\n\n        Returns:\n            torch.Tensor: The input sequence concatenated with the generated tokens.\n        """\n        # TODO: Implement this\n        raise NotImplementedError("The generate method must be implemented by a subclass.")\n\n    @abstractmethod\n    def get_num_parameters(self, non_embedding: bool = True) -> int:\n        """\n        Calculates and returns the total number of trainable parameters in the model.\n\n        The contract:\n        - Must iterate through `self.parameters()` to count them.\n        - If `non_embedding` is True, it must exclude the token embedding parameters\n          from the count, as is common practice in some literature.\n        - Must return an integer representing the total count.\n\n        Args:\n            non_embedding (bool): If True, excludes token embedding parameters from the count.\n\n        Returns:\n            int: The number of trainable parameters.\n        """\n        # TODO: Implement this\n        raise NotImplementedError("The get_num_parameters method must be implemented by a subclass.")\n\n\n# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# Data Loader Interface\n# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nclass MiniTextDataLoader(ABC):\n    """\n    Abstract base class for a data loader that processes a text file.\n\n    This interface defines the necessary methods for loading text data,\n    tokenizing it, and serving it in batches suitable for training a language model.\n    """\n\n    @abstractmethod\n    def __init__(self, data_path: str, block_size: int, batch_size: int):\n        """\n        Initializes the data loader.\n\n        The contract:\n        - Must read the text data from the file specified by `data_path`.\n        - Must create a vocabulary and mappings (char-to-int and int-to-char).\n        - Must tokenize the entire dataset into a single tensor of indices.\n        - Must split the data into training and validation sets (e.g., 90%/10%).\n        - Must store `block_size` and `batch_size` for use in `get_batch`.\n\n        Args:\n            data_path (str): The path to the input text file.\n            block_size (int): The sequence length for each training example.\n            batch_size (int): The number of sequences in a single batch.\n        """\n        # TODO: Implement this\n        raise NotImplementedError("The __init__ method must be implemented by a subclass.")\n\n    @abstractmethod\n    def get_batch(self, split: str = \'train\') -> tuple[torch.Tensor, torch.Tensor]:\n        """\n        Retrieves a single batch of data.\n\n        The contract:\n        - Must accept a `split` argument, which can be \'train\' or \'val\'.\n        - Must randomly sample starting positions for `batch_size` sequences from the\n          corresponding data split (train or validation).\n        - Must return two tensors, `x` and `y`.\n        - `x` (inputs) must contain sequences of `block_size` length.\n        - `y` (targets) must contain the subsequent token for each position in `x`.\n        - The shape of both returned tensors must be (batch_size, block_size).\n\n        Args:\n            split (str): The data split to sample from (\'train\' or \'val\').\n\n        Returns:\n            tuple[torch.Tensor, torch.Tensor]: A tuple containing the input and target tensors.\n        """\n        # TODO: Implement this\n        raise NotImplementedError("The get_batch method must be implemented by a subclass.")\n\n    @abstractmethod\n    def get_vocab_size(self) -> int:\n        """\n        Returns the size of the vocabulary.\n\n        The contract:\n        - Must return the total number of unique tokens (characters) found in the dataset.\n\n        Returns:\n            int: The vocabulary size.\n        """\n        # TODO: Implement this\n        raise NotImplementedError("The get_vocab_size method must be implemented by a subclass.")\n\n\n# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# Trainer Interface\n# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nclass MiniTrainer(ABC):\n    """\n    Abstract base class for a training and evaluation manager.\n\n    This interface encapsulates the logic for the training loop, optimizer setup,\n    learning rate scheduling, and evaluation.\n    """\n\n    @abstractmethod\n    def __init__(self, model: MiniGPTModel, data_loader: MiniTextDataLoader, config: dict):\n        """\n        Initializes the trainer.\n\n        The contract:\n        - Must store the `model` and `data_loader` instances.\n        - Must use the `config` dictionary to set up training parameters like\n          learning rate, weight decay, etc.\n        - Must instantiate an optimizer (e.g., `torch.optim.AdamW`).\n        - May optionally set up a learning rate scheduler.\n\n        Args:\n            model (MiniGPTModel): The model to be trained.\n            data_loader (MiniTextDataLoader): The data loader providing training batches.\n            config (dict): A dictionary containing training-specific hyperparameters.\n        """\n        # TODO: Implement this\n        raise NotImplementedError("The __init__ method must be implemented by a subclass.")\n\n    @abstractmethod\n    def train(self, num_iterations: int):\n        """\n        Executes the main training loop.\n\n        The contract:\n        - Must loop for `num_iterations`.\n        - In each iteration, it must:\n            1. Fetch a batch of data using `data_loader.get_batch(\'train\')`.\n            2. Perform a forward pass through the `model` to get logits and loss.\n            3. Zero out gradients in the optimizer.\n            4. Perform a backward pass to compute gradients.\n            5. Update the model weights using the optimizer.\n        - Should include periodic logging of the training loss.\n\n        Args:\n            num_iterations (int): The total number of training steps to perform.\n        """\n        # TODO: Implement this\n        raise NotImplementedError("The train method must be implemented by a subclass.")\n\n    @abstractmethod\n    @torch.no_grad()\n    def evaluate(self, num_batches: int = 10) -> float:\n        """\n        Computes and returns the average loss on the validation set.\n\n        The contract:\n        - Must operate in `torch.no_grad()` mode.\n        - Must set the model to evaluation mode (`model.eval()`).\n        - Must iterate for `num_batches`, fetching validation data each time.\n        - Must accumulate the loss over these batches and return the mean loss.\n        - Must restore the model to training mode (`model.train()`) before exiting.\n\n        Args:\n            num_batches (int): The number of validation batches to average over.\n\n        Returns:\n            float: The average validation loss.\n        """\n        # TODO: Implement this\n        raise NotImplementedError("The evaluate method must be implemented by a subclass.")\n\n── Module behaviors ──\n[\n  {\n    "name": "MiniGPTConfig",\n    "description": "A dataclass holding all essential hyperparameters for the MiniGPT model.",\n    "depends_on": [],\n    "interface_sketch": "from dataclasses import dataclass\\n\\n@dataclass\\nclass M